{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600568/1930110201/0410.xml":{"full_text":"WASHINGTON\nTAXI INSURANCE\nINJUNCTION TO BE\nARGUEDTGMORROW\nUtilities Group Seeks to Fix\nFinancial Responsibility\nfar Industry.\nINDEPENDENT OWNER\nHALTED RECENT ORDER\nj\nCommission Insists Act of 1913\nGives It Power It Seeks to\nExercise.\nThe question of the power of the I\nPublic Utilities Commission to insist!\non financial responsibility of these en-!\ngated in the taxicab industry will be\nargued before the District Court of Ap- I\npeals tomorrow. This question was de- i\nelded against the commission by the\nDistrict Supreme Court, which issued\na permanent injunction restraining the\ncommission from enforcing its order\nNo. 823 of December 30, 1929. in which 1\nthe requirement of financial responsi- 1\nblllty was established.\nThis requirement, according to the;\norder, could be met in three ways\u2014by\na statement disclosing ability to pay all\ndamages which may result from any\nand all accidents due to the negligent\nuse and operation of the taxicab; by\nfiling with the commission a security,\nIndemnity, or bond guaranteeing the\npayment of such damages, or by taking\ninsurance to a reasonable amount the\noperator's liability to pay such damages\nIndependent Owner Sues.\nWhen it was sought to put this order\nInto effect, an independent taxi owner,\nF B. Smith, sued out and obtained\nan injunction against 't in the trial\ncourt. The commission appealed. In\nits brief, the commission insists that\nthe public utilities act of March 4,\n1913, although not specifically making\nprovision for financial responsibility of\ntaxicab owners, was broad enough to\ngive the commission the powers which\nit. now seeks to exercise. The brief\nquotes one paragraph of the act which\nstates that \"every public utility is re\nquired to obey the lawful orders of\nthe commission,\u201d and another which\nstates that \"every public utility doing\nbusiness within the District of Colum-.\nbia is required to furnish service and\nfacilities reasonably safe and adequate\nand in all respects just and reasonable.\u201d\nUnder this it is contended that \u201csafe\u201d\nmeans free from harm, injury, or risk,\nand that service and facilities are not\nin all respects just and reasonable\nwhere the victim of the negligence of\nthe operator and owner of a taxicab\ncannot satisfy a just judgment ren\ndered against him by reason of his\nnegligence.\nRoberts to Argue Case.\nThe case is to be argued for the\ncommission by Assistant Corporation\nCounsel William A. Roberts and Robert\nE. Lynch. The commission has been\nseeking an effective control over the\ntaxicab Industry for the past year,\nwithout very much in the way of prac\ntical results. One police regulation\nrecently adopted by the District Com\nmissioners has made it possible for the\ncommission to enforce its order that all\ncabs on the streets must carry, painted\non the body, the name or trade style\nof the operator and the serial number\nof the cab. The commission is now'\n.engaged in strenuous efforts to secure\nenforcement of its orders relating to\nthe filing of monthly statistical reports\nby the taxi concerns by suing them for\nfines in all cases where the reports are\nnot made. None of these bases, how\never, has yet been tried. Last year the\ncommission sought specific legislation\nfrom Congress giving it control of the\ntaxi Industry in these various par\nticulars, but the act was not passed.\nBATES WILL ADDRESS\nFRIENDS\u2019 FORUM TONIGHT\n\u201cA Protective Penal Poller\u201d I, 1\nt\nSubject of TJ. 8. Bureau of\nPrisons Director.\nSanford Bates, director of the Bu\nreau of Prisons of the Department of\nJustice, will talk on \u201cA Protective\nPenal Policy\u201d at the Friend*' Forum\nthis evening at 1811 I street Mr\nBates has had charge of all Federal\nprisons gnd correctional institutions\nsince early in 1929.\nDuring the past Summer Mr. Bates\nwas elected a vice president of the In- 1\ntematlonal Prison Conference, which\nhe attended at Prague. The forum\nmeetings are at 8 o\u2019clock. The speakei\nNovember 24 will be Dr. Henry T.\nHodgkin, head of Pendle Hill School,\nand December 14, Miss Grace Abbott,\nchief of the United States Children s\nBureau, will speak.\nMISS WILSON TO TALK\nAT Y. W. C. A. MEETING\nSpeaker Spent 30 Tears Doing \"Y\"\nWork in India and U. S. Before\nBecoming Minister.\nMiss Elisabeth Wilson, pioneer Y. W.\nC. A. secretary and editor, will speak\nat the first monthly world-fellowship\nWinter meeting to be held tomorrow\nafternoon at 12 o'clock at the Y. W.\nC. A. headquarters here. Mrs. Robert\nLansing, chairman of the Hospitality\nCommittee of the Y. W. C. A., will pre\nside.\nMiss Wilson, who has spent 30 years\nin \"Y\u201d work in this country and India,\nand who retired to become a minister\nin the Methodist Church, will speak on\n\u201cWhat Young Women in India Are\nDoing Through the Y. W. C. A.\"\nSaturday night, it was announced yes\nterday. Miss Wilson will be the speaker\nat the all-association dinner to be\ngiven by the members of the local staff\nof the Y. W. C. A. in her honor.\nFLORIST IS CHARGED\nWITH DRUNK DRIVING\nOccupant of Machine Is Cut About\nHead When Car Crashes\nPole.\nCharles Morris. 39-year-old florist of\nWalker's Chapel, Va., was arrested on\na charge of driving while drunk yester\nday afternoon following an accident in\nwhich an occupant of the machine he\nwas driving suffered minor cuts about\nthe head.\nMorris was taken into custody by Po\nliceman Charles Clay of the seventh\nSrectnct, when his automobile crashed\nito a telephone pole in the 3800 block\nof Sherrier place. Emery Oliver, 45\nyears old. of 2027 H street, was taker\nto Georgetown Hospital.\nMorris obtained his release on *1 00C\nbond.\n6-Year-Old Falls\ni j\nTwo Stories While\nAt Play in Home|\nDorothy Craig Is in Gal\ni linger Hospital With\nInternal Injuries.\nTumbling from a second story win\ndow of her home, in which she had\nbeen playing, little Dorothy Craig. 6\nyears old, of 510 Eighth street south\neast, was Injured seriously shortly be- j\nfore 5 o'clock yesterday afternoon.\nThe little girl is in Gallinger Hos- j\npital with serious internal injuries and\nscalp wounds.\nDorothy, according to hospital au\nthorities, was sitting in the window\nplaying when she lost her balance and\nfell from the sill to the groi nd. 25 feet\nbelow. Her screams brought her\nmother, Mrs. Lottie Craig, who imme- j\ndiately called police for help.\nThe fifth precinct patrol wagon re- j\nsponded and took the girl to the\nhospital.\nPROSPERITY DRIVE\nAIDED BV PASTORS\nj\nBuy-Now Campaign Will Be\nFully Launched Tomorrow\nto Help Jobless.\nA plea for prosperity promotion\nthrough prompt purchasing will be\nsounded from church pulpits of the city\ntoday as part of the \"buy-now-for-bet\nter-business\u201d campaign of the Wash- j\nington Chamber of Commerce, which j\nwill be fully launched through many j\nmediums tomorrow, backed by a cen-\ntral committee of citizens from all walks\nof life. j\nBy radio, the press, the screen, bill-\nboards, letterheads, in luncheon and\nafter-dinner speeches, at citizens' meet- j\nings the words of prosperity will be\nspoken to the people.\nA prospectus of the campaign was\ngiven last night by Charles W\u2019. Darr,\nformer president of the chamber, and\nGeorge A. G. Wood, chairman of the\n\u201cBuy-now-for better business\" Cam\npaign Committee.\nExpect Public Response.\nEmphasizing the fact that the enter\nprise is a community-w:de affair, Mr.\nDarr declared, in a talk broadcast over j\nStation WMAL, that the sponsors of the\ncampaign expect it to \u201cgrow like the j\ntraditional snow ball.\u201d\n\u201cIt is particularly fitting,\u201d Mr. Darr\nsaid, \u201cthat the \u2018buy-now-for-better\nbusiness' campaign should be inaugu\nrated during the week covered by the\nsixth annual Industrial Exposition of\nthe Washington Chamber of Commerce\nat the Washington Auditorium. This\ntrade show will furnish a graphic pic\nture of locally made and locally dis\ntributed products, increased sale of\nwhich will be of material aid in hasten\ning business revival in the pistrict and\nelsewhere.\n\u201cExperience has revealed to us one\nsure way to get over the effects of a\nbusiness depression. That way is to\nwrite off and to forget our real or im-\naginary losses and to settle down again j\nto the kind of work which gets results\nand creates new and still greater j\nvalues.\n\"In this connection it is often said\nthat there are two ways to get ahead\u2014 j\n<1 to earn more, or <2) to save more.\nBoth of these alms are good when not j\ncarried to excess. Too much concen- I\ntratlon on earnings makes us neglect j\nour duties to our family, friends and j\ncommunity and leads to unhappiness j\nThe saving instinct, when overempha- i\nsized by the many, reduces community j\nbuying power and this results in lower\nwages and smaller profits.\n\u201cThe sponsors of the 'Buy-Now-for-\nBetter-Business\u2019 movement are not try-1\ning to start a spending ogry to fill the J\ncoffers of our shopkeepers. On the con- j\ntrarv, they are strongly opposed to a\ncareless and ill-advised expenditure ol\nhard-earned dollars. Such a course I\nI would harm rather than help the re- j\ncovery of business.\"\nThe speaker brought out the following j\nfive points, which he suggested might j\nbe followed to offset underexpenditure,\nwhich he explained is quite as harmful j\nin its results as is the overexpenditure j\ncharacteristic of a period of inflation J\nProfit by Past Lessons.\n\u201c1. Study past expenditures and de-j\ntermine which were wise and which\nwere unwise.\n\u201c2. Draw up a budget for future j\nspending dropping all items found to\nbe unnecessary.\n\"3. Compare this budget with annual\nincome and add or subtract enough\ni money to bring the total within the In\ncome limit with a proper margin of\nsaving.\n\"4. Study current advertisements to j\ndiscover how to spend money for items i\nIncluded in the budget to the best pos-\nsible advantage\n\u201c5 Having decided what we need, i\nwhat we can afford to spend, and how j\nwe can spend mo6t advantageously.\nthen start in and do buying now.\u201d\nI \u201cThe Job Registration Bureau of the\nI chamber has been inaugurated as an i\nemergency measure to help us meet the j\nchallenge of unemployment and to\nstimulate the discovery and registration\nof employment opportunities of every\nj possible type.\nI \u201cThis undertaking, however, is a tem\ni porary one which may be taken over at\nany moment by some other public or\nj semi-public agency.\u201d\nj Does Not Blame Polities.\nJ Mr. Wood speaking over station\nj WRC during ihe Washington Gas Light\n5 1 Co. hour, did not blame politics, the\nj tariff or \u201cany other phase of the outer\nr workings of a political party\" for the\n1 1 present industrial pli\u00dfht. but money\nwhich got beyond the reach of business\nJ and was used largely to make possible\n-1 fictitious values of securities.\u201d\nr j Speaking in an encouraging vein the\ns, Campaign Committee chairman voiced\nf the belief that this faltering was only\nfor a brief spell. \"We will prove to the\nrest of the world that America leads in\nthe welfare of its citizens. That means\nthe creation of jobs by all who have\ni the means of buying now and contln-\nI umg to buy on the scale and standard\nnow so well established.\"\nArrangement has been completed\n1 with stations WRC and WMAL for a\nseries of radio talks throughout the\nweek.\nBOY SWALLOWS PENNY\n1\na Johnny Murphy, 3 years old. last\ne night swallowed a penny which he found\nt under the carpet while playing on the\nfloor of his home at 1228 Montello ave\nnue northeast. The child\u2019s parents\ncame in just in time to see him gulp\nd down the coin.\nk Johnny was rushed to Casualty Hos\n-5 pital, where he was attended by Dr.\nn Louis Jlmal. The doctor learned that\nJohnny was suffering no ill effects from\n0 the penny and sent him home with in\nstructions to report lat<*s for treatment.\n\u00a9ht pinulay fto?\nWASHINGTON, D. C., SUNDAY MORNING, NOVEMBER 2, 1930.\nCHISHOLM IS NAMED\nON PARKWAY BOARD\nTO PURCHASE LAND!\nI\nTwo Members Who Are\nChosen Will Select Third for\nMemorial Group.\nMT. VERNON HIGHWAY\nBEGINS TO TAKE SHAPE\nControl Over 1,641 Acres of Prop\nerty Yet to Be Acquired for\nProject.\nCapt. E. N. Chisolm. jr., engineer of\nthe National Capital Park and Plan\nning Commission, was designated yes-'\nterday by Lieut. Col. U. S. Grant, 3d,!\nthe commission\u2019s vice chairman and\nexecutive officer, as his nominee on the\nBoard of Appraisal that will purchase\nland in Virginia under the George j\nWashigton Memorial Parkway program.\nIndexing keen interest of Washing\ntonians in the parkway development,\nthe commission has been deluged by re\nquests for an illustrated pamphlet de\nscriptive of the whole project, which it\nhas just issued.\nWill Name Third Member.\nThe board of supervisors of Arlington\nCounty, Va.. recently named Keith A.\nBrumback, Virginia real estate man, as\ni its nominee to co-operate with the\nI Planning Commission. Capt. Chisolm\nand Mr. Brumback have met informally\nand have agreed on the name of a third\nman to serve on the Board of Appraisal,\ni His identity is being withheld for the\npresent. In order that the State and\nFederal Governments and the county\nauthorities will get full value for their\nmoney, in the purchase of prospective\ni parkway property, the Board of Ap\npraisal is being set up. As soon as the\nj third member ha* been officially se\nlected the board will begin to function.\nInformation on land-purchasing activity\nis held confidential.\nIn the purchase of land on the Mary\nland side of the Potomac River, south\ni w \u00bbrd of Great Falls to Fort Washing\nton, Md., it is expected that the co\noperation of the Maryland National\nCapital Park and Planning Commission\nwill be obtained, as well as the State\nand county authorities.\nThe first link in the George Wash\nington Memorial Parkway is nearing\ncompletion, as the Mount Vernon\nMemorial Highway. The Fort Drive,\nthat will link up a group of historic\nI Civil War forts encircling the city, will\nlikely be utilized a* the highway for\nthe parkway through Washington.\nParkway Takes Shape.\nA great new development will be\nopened up between Blue Plains, D. C\u201e\nand Fort Washington, the Army post\nthat is remembered as the one where\nL Enfant constructed part of the forti\nfications. A new arterial highway will\nbe constructed in that region, to afford\nmotorists a beautiful driveway along\na little-known section of Maryland,\ndown to Piscataway Creek, eastward of\nMarshall Hall.\nThe pamphlet asserts that the com\nmission has already acquired lands\nfor almost half the distance between\nthe Anacostia River in Washington and\nFort Washington, and Is now engaged\nunder other authority in acquisition of\nj lands along the Potomac above the city\nwhich lie within the District of Co\nl lumbia.\u201d\nThe George Washington Memorial\nParkway is taking tangible shape ii.\nI the vicinity of Mount Vernon, where\ngrading work has been accomplished\ni and the groundwork laid for a large\nI parking space at this terminus of the\nboulevard. The United States Engineer I\nj Office, under the direction of Maj. Jo-\nI seph D. Arthur, jr., district engineer\nlor the War Department for the Wash\n-1 ington area, is completing the hydraulic\npipe line dredging work, in throwing\nI the roadbed across the various inlets I\nbetween Washington and Mount Ver\nnon. This is accomplished by pumping\nup sand and gravel from the bottom of\nj the Potomac River by means of a pow\nerful hydraulic pipe line dredge.\nPaving Scheduled Early in 1931.\nPaving of the Mount Vernon Me\nmorial Highway is expected to be un\ndertaken early in the new year, as\nsoon as the weather settles to permit\nI pouring of concrete. The construction\nof this highway Is proceeding under\ndirection of the Bureau of Public Roads\nof the Department of Agriculture.\nOfficials of the bureau yesterday fur-\nI nished The Star with this picture of\ni the present state of the development:\nHydraulic work on four of the \u201cfills\u201d\u2014\nplacing a streak of earth for the future\nI roadbeds across the water inlets that\ncross the right of way of the highway\ni \u2014has been about completed. Work is\nproceeding on the last of these \u201cfills,\" j\ni that at Hunting Creek Grading work\nj on dry land is now about 70 per cent\nj completed.\nThree bridges\u2014at the Fort Hunt\nj overpass, at the Wellington Villa under\npass and at the Southern Railway in\ndustrial overpass at Alexandria \u2014are\nnow nearly complete,\nj With reference to the fiscal features\niof the George Washington Memorial\nParkway, the pamphlet of the National\nCapital Park and Planning Commis\nsion explains: \u201cFor the acquisition of\ncontrol. Congress has authorized ap\npropriation of $7,500,000 and has al\nready appropriated $1,000,000 which Is\navailable for land purchases when co\noperation of other parties Is forthcom\ning. Under the Capper-Cramton act,\nthe whole cost of maintaining and\npolicing the park areas after acquisition\nwill be borne by the Federal Govern\nment.\nCost Is Provided For.\n\u201cCongress has provided that Federal\nappropriations may be expended by the\ni National Capital Park and Planning\nj Commission for any unit of the project\nupon receipt of definite commitments\nfrom the State of Maryland or Virginia,\nor political subdivisions thereof, or from\nother responsible sources for one-half\nthe cost of acquiring\u2019 the land.\n\u2018Congress has further offered to ad\nvance the whole cost of acquiring any\nunit upon agreement with either State\nor any political subdivision thereof for\nreimbursement to the United States of\none-half the cost without interest with\nin eight years.\u201d\nThe Mount Vernon Memorial High- 1\nway will run from the Arlington Me- j\nmortal Bridge to Mount. Vc rnon, a dis-\ntance of 15 miles, and will traverse a\ncountry rich in historic interest, terrni\nnatu.g at the old nome of the Father\nof His Country.\nThe commission, in its publication,\nt points out that \u201ccontrol over various\nI ureas, totaling about 1,641 acres and\nlying between the Mount Vernon Me\nmortal Highway and the river, is still\ni to be acquired. The most important of\nthese areas are at Little Hunting Creek,\nWellington and Wellington Villa, near\nDyke, north of Alexandria and at Hunt\ners and Gravelly Points.\nt Along the upper Potomac River pre\ni liminary sunyys by the commission \u201cin\ndicate a desirable park area of over 269\narr-s this portion of the river In\nI \u20141\nHOW ARLINGTON BRIDGE AREA WILL LOOK UNDER PARKWAY PLAN\nj\nmaiEF^z-' *_ \u00a3^%\u00a3*aSF^M\nThe above drawing shows the treatment proposed for the Arlington Bridge area of the Potomac Valley in the George Washington Memorial Parkway plan.\nr\nPOLICEMAN SAVED\nWHEN PISTOL FAILS\nColored Man\u2019s Gun Snaps in\nOfficer Clay\u2019s Face\nFive Times.\nA defective pistol saved Policeman\nHenry Clay of the seventh precinct\nlast night from almost certain death.\nWhile attempting to arrest Louis Wil\nliams, 52 years old, colored, a pistol\nheld by Williams snapped five times In\nClay's face. Examination of the gun\nshowed that the hammer of the weapon\nfailed to dent the five cartridge caps.\nCalled to a house in the 1300 block\nof Twenty-seventh street by an anony\nmous telephone call that reported a\nbrawl in progress. Clay walked into a\nroom to find Clarence Bell. 40-year-old\ncolored man, lying on the floor severely\ncut, and Williams standing nearby with\ndrawn pistol.\n\"Don\u2019t you move. You\u2019re in my\nhouse and I\u2019ll shoot,\" Clay quoted Wil\nliams as saying.\nDisregarding the order. Clay said he\nadvanced toward Williams, who began\nto pull the \"rigger of the gun. The\ncartridges failed to explode. Williams\nattacked the policeman with his fists\nwhen the pistol failed to fire, it was\nsaid, but was overpowered by Clay after\na brief struggle and taken to the seventh\nprecinct after Clay had arranged for\nBell\u2019s removal to the hospital.\nWilliams told police he lived at the\nhouse were the stabbing occurred,\nbut an investigation revealed that he\ndid not.\nfellowship\u2019rules\nIN LAW ANNOUNCED\nApplications to Be Received Until\nMarch 1 in Teacher and Student\nClassifications.\nThe Division of International Law of\nthe Carnegie Endowment for Intema\nj tional Peace last week announced regu\nlations governing fellowships in inter\nnational law which will be awarded by\nthe Committee on International Law\nFellowships for the academic year\n1931-2.\nThe fellowships, which have been\nestablished by the trustees of the en- I\ndowment to provide teachers competent\nin giving instruction in international\nlaw' and related subjects, as an aid to\ncolleges and universities in extending\nand improving study and teaching of\nthese subjects, are awarded in two j\nclasses, teachers\u2019 fellowships and stu\ndents\u2019 fellowships\nApplications will be received up to\nMarch 1, 1931, it was announced by the\ncommittee through Dr. James Brown\nScott, director.\nENGINEERS CELEBRATE\nDinner Planned November 19 to\nObserve Anniversary.\nThe twenty-flfth anniversary of the\nfounding of the Washington Society\nI of Engineers will be celebrated with a\nI dinner of the entire membership of\nthe society at the Mayflower Hotel No\nj vember 19, it was announced yester\nday by F. A. Hunnewell, president.\nThe Washington Society of Engineers\nhas a membership of over 700 profes\nsional engineers engaged in all phases\nof engineering work. Its officers and\ndirectors are: F A. Hunnewell, presi- j\ndent; W. E. Parker, vice president; W.\ng Garland, treasurer; Paul C. Whitney,\nsecretary; C. H. Birdseye. E. C. Gil- i\nlette. C. B. Hawley, A B. McDaniel, I\nB J. Peterson. Starr Truscott. D C\nWalser and C. C Witt, directors.\n\u201cRace for Gentlemen\u2019\u2019 a Success.\nROUEN, France (A*).\u2014 A race for\ngentlemen, in which the contestants j\nwore evening clothes, high hats, gloves\nand a buttonhole bouquet and carried\ncanes was held here, the winner cov- j\nering three miles in 35 minutes.\nArlington County and approximately\n2.460 acres in Fairfax County.\u201d\nCircuit Drive to Be Provided.\nOn the Maryland shore in the lower\nPotomac, the commission explains that\nits plans \"call for a parkway from the\nDistrict of Columbia at Oxon Run. i\nalong the river to Fort Foote, to Indian\nQueen Bluff, and then on a fill across\nBroad Creek and along the shore to j\nFort Washington.\n\u2018The completion of a Federal-aid\nhighway along such a route would make\npossible a circuit drive of 28.5 miles\nvia the Mount Vernon Highway, across\nthe river by ferry at Fort Washington\nand return.\u201d the commission points out.\n\"The right of way for this Fort Wash\nington Parkway is designed to have a\nminimum width of 250 feet and is es\ntimated to involve acquisition of about\n341 acres\u201d\nOn the upper Potomac, the commis\nsion asserts that \u201cbetween Conduit road\nand the river (omitting Glen Echo and\npart of Cabin John subdivisions) ap\nproximately 3,546 acres are to be ac\nquired. This portion of the project in\ncludes the Chesapeake Ohio Canal\n(abandoned) to Point of Rocks, which\nis proposed to restore for pleasure boat\ning. The proposed parkway la deigned\nto follow the north bank of the canal\nbeyond Cabin John.\u2019)\nU. S. Folk Songs Gathered\nDr. R. W. Gordon Makes Thorough Study of Origin\nand Development of Tunes and Words for Library\nof Congress \u2014Wealth of Material Found.\nAmerica\u2019s vast store of folk songs\nis being preserved, collected and studied\nat the Library of Congress.\nThe work is under the direction of\nDr. R. W. Gordon, who is finding in\nthe oblivion of thousands of old hymn\nbooks the songs of forgotten yesterdays,\nand. with infinite labor, tracing them\nback to their origins and variations\nHe also is perfecting and assembling\napparatus for collecting American folk\nsongs in the field from persons who\nstill remember them.\nWealth of Folk Songs.\nThe United States, Gordon says, ha'\nthe greatest wealth of folk songs of\nany country, since it inherited practi\ncally all those of England. Scotland and\nIreland besides adding some types of\nits own. such as the Negro spiritual.\nThe very nature of a folk song, Gordon\npoints out, makes it an invaluable in\nstrument for unearthing the social his\ntory of a people, since men and women\nsing spontaneously of those things\nwhich are closest to their hearts, and\nslight variations of words or music may\nshow important fundamental changes.\nFor, says Gordon, the first test of\na folk song is that it has arisen spon\ntaneously, without any specific author.\nWhen some author deliberately takes a\nfolk son\" and, by a stroke of genius,\nstabilizes its fcrm. it cea'es to be a\nfolk song. Thus Burns took songs like\n\"Auld Lang Syne,\u201d snatches of which\nprobably had been floating around the\nScotch countryside for years, and put\nthem in permanent form so that they\ncea'ed to be folk songs and became part\nof his poetry. Such songs as \"My Old\nKentucky Home\" and \u201cSwanee River.\"\nhe says, are by no means folk songs, but\ndefinite literary and musical works of\none man, although based on folk\nthemes.\nDetective Ability Needed.\nTracing real folk songs to their origin\nrequires almost infinite labor and pa\ntience. An example of the folk song\nwhose history Gordon has unearthed\nbit by bit in the dusty old song books\nin \u201cJohn Brown's Body.\"\n\"John Brown's body lies a-moul\ndering in the grave.\nBut his soul goes marching on\nSo sang the boys in blue as they\npoured out of the cities and villages of\nthe North in 1861.\nThe emotion-stirring Glory, glory*\nhallelujah\u201d of the chorus was a potent\nthing in stirring up fighting fer\\or. It\nhas come down as a fixed part of the\npicture of the Civil W>r The song\npassed from lif to lip and variations\nand new verses w r ere fitted to the tune.\nSoon the soldiers were singing.\n\u2022\u2018We'll hang Jeff Davis to a sour\napple tree.\nGlory, glory, hallelujah.\u2019\nDixie Answers Challenge.\nEven in Dixie this spontaneous song\nwas taken up with the answering chal-\nhang Abe Lincoln to a sour\napple tree,\nGlory, glory, hallelujah.\u201d\nAnd back again In the North the\nmoving chorus inspired Julia Ward\nj Howe to write \u201cThe Battle Hymn of\nj the Republic.\u201d thus giving the appar\nently spontaneous war song a fixed form\nin literature.\nAnd in one of the Massachusetts\nregiments there was an unfortunate\nfellow named John Brown, upon whom\nthe song was fixed in vigorous burlesque\nand passed from regiment to regiment\nlin an unending variation of verses.\nThe hickless private was the \u2018\u2018made\nmoiselle from Armentieres\" of the Civil\nWar.\nOdd Quirks Revealed.\nNow Gordon\u2019s researches in the old\nand forgotten hymnals and song col\nlections in the library files have revealed\nthe strange circumstance that this song\nwas ready and waiting for some time\nbefore the John Brown who was hanged\nfor the Harpers Ferry raid had come to\npublic notice. It was practically a case\nof a song about an event being written\nbefore the event happened.\nBack in the ola Kentucky camp meet\ning days, Gordon finds, there was a\nspiritual which ran as follows:\n\"O, brother, will you meet me\nOn Canaan\u2019s happy shore;\nBy the grace of God I\u2019ll meet you\nOn Canaan\u2019s happy shore.\nThere we\u2019ll shout and give Him glory.\nThere we\u2019ll shout and give Him glory.\nThere w'e'U shout and give Him glory.\nOn Canaan's happy shore.\u201d\nFrom this forgotten hymn, apparent\nly so far removed, the trail leads di\nrectly to \"John Brown's body\u201d and.\nthence, to the \"Battle Hymn of the Re\npublic.\u201d But the job of tracing it was\na marvelous bit of literary and musical\ndetective work.\nSong Preceded Event.'\nGordon found this song first in a\nprinted collection of camp-meeting\nhymns which appeared in 1809, when\nthe John Brown of history was a boy.\nIt had probably been in existence, un\nprinted, for years. It was not accom\npanied by music.\nThen it appears in various hymnals\nwith music, but not the tune of John\nBrown's body. Changes were being\nintroduced in the words. In a hymnal\nof 1858 appeared tire lines:\nWhen this poor body lies a-moul\nering in the tomb,\nMy soul\u2019s safe at home.\nApparently verse after verse of the\noriginal, merely repetitions with slight\nvariations, sprang up spontaneously in\nthe emotion-charged atmosphere of a\ncamp meeting.\nThus the song could be continued in\ndefinitely, ascending all the time to a\nhigher and higher emotional pitch. Just\nthe same way the Civil War soldiers\nfirst \"hanged Jeff Davis\u201d and then all\nthe rest of the Southern officials and\ngenerals, the Confederates doing the\nsame for Lincoln and so on down the\nlist.\nFinal Result Is Hymn.\nThen, in April, 1859, a hymnal was\nprinted containing the words with the\nmusic of \"John Brown s Body,\u201d the first\nappearance in musical literature, al- j\nthough it must have been a part of\nthe folk music for a long time.\nAnd John Brown was not hanged\nuntil December, 1859. The old tune and\nlines of the hymn were simply fitted on\nthe event.\n\"Oh, brother, will you meet me?\u201d j\nhe compares to the trunk of a tree.\nThen the coupling it with the \"Glory,\nglory, hallelujah\" chorus and music be\ncomes a branch from the trunk. Ap- j\nplying it to John Brown becomes an\nother limb branching off the first, while\nthe \"hanging Jeff Davis\u201d version is\nanother branch. And the clownish,\nobscene and other adventures of John\nBrown, the Yankee private, become still\nanother sub-branch from the Harpers\nFerry John Brown branch. All these\nbranches sprouted naturally, but the\n\"Battle Hymn of the Republic\u201d was a\ndeliberate graft on the folk song tree.\nUntil this last step the song had no\nauthor, but amounted to a growing se\nries of spontaneous verses which sprang\nto the lips of emotionally-stirred crowds.\nCRIPPLED CHILDREN\nCAN GET EDUCATION\nSpecial Classes Are Established in\n85 American Cities; Civic\nOrganizations Help.\n\nBy the Associated Pres*.\nSpecial classes for crippled children\nhave been established by public school\nsystems of 85 cities in the United\nStates to aid them to secure an edu\ncation equal to that of the healthy\nchild.\nA study made by the Office of Educa-!\ntion in the Department of the Interior\nhas shown that crippled children num\nber one for every 400 of the general\npopulation and disclosed that the public\nschools of the Nation are giving more\nattention to the needs of crippled chil\ndren than ever before.\nThe first public school facilities for\ncrippled children were established by\nChicago in 1899, which now has four\nschools where more than 1.600 crippled\nchildren receive instruction.\nThe Order of the Mystic Shrine, the\nRotarlan. Kiwanis and other business\ni men\u2019s clubs, the Junior League and the\nRed Cross, with other organizations,\nhave aided the schools in their efforts.\nART IN ADVERTISING\nj TO BE SUBJECT OF TALK\n\u2019I\nGordan C. Aymar of New York to\nAddress Washington Club\nTuesday.\n\"The Value of Art in Advertising\u201d\nwill be the subject of Gordon C. Avmar\nof the Blackman Co. of New York be\n-1 fore the Advertising Club of Washing-\nton at Its Tuesday\nluncheon at 12:30\no\u2019clock in the au\nditorium of the\nNational Press\nClub.\nMr. Aymar\u2019s ad\ndress will be illus\ntrated with views\nof samples of ad\nvertising art in\ncolors. Newspa\npers and maga- j\nzines have given j\nsuch increasing i\nmanifestations of\nthe aid of art in f\npublic announce- j\nments. it is ex-,\nplained, that\nPresident James\nMr. Armir.\nW. S. Hardv and the directors of the\nAdvertising Club selected Mr. Aymar 1\nto make the presentation of this phase j\nof advertising.\nAn invitation has been accepted by\nthe art schools of Washington for their\nj faculties and students to attend. Stu\ndents will be admitted upon presenta\ntion of a regular student card or letter\nfrom the institutions invited.\nDIVISION CHIEF NAMED\nWalter C. Thurston of Colorado, j\nUnited States Foreign Service officer\nwho has served as assistant chief of the\nDivision of Latln-American Affairs at\nthe State Department since April. 1929,\nhas been appointed chief of that divi\nsion to fill the vacancy occasioned by\nthe recent appointment of Dana C.\nMunro as United States Minister to\nHaiti.\nMr. Thurston entered the Foreign\nService in 1914, and has served succes\nsively in Mexico, Guatemala, the State\nDepartment; Bern, Switzerland; San\nJose. Costa Rica; London. Nicaragua,\nBrasil. Portugal, Cuba and this city.\nGENERAL NEWS\nLIQUOR INDICTMENT\nFORM IS CHANGED\nNew Method Evolved by\nRover Approved by Decision\nof Justice Gordon.\nPending action by the District Court\nI of Appeals on the decision of Justice\nPeyton Gordon of the District Supreme\nCourt that an indictment against Ed\nward E. Denison, Representative from\nIllinois, charged with possession of\nliquor was bad because it did not ad\nvise the accused of what he was\ncharged, United States Attorney Leo A.\nRover has evolved a new form of in\ndictment in cases involving the sale\nand possession of liquor.\nThe new form of indictment was at\ntacked yesterday before Justice Gordon\nand met with his approval, as shown\nby his decision to dismiss a demurrer\nagainst it. The new form sets forth\nthe names of th- persons to whom sales\nwere made and the dates and places.\nThe indictment held good by Justice\nGordon charges Edward Tipton, 817-819\nFourteenth street, with sale and pos\nsession of liquor. It is in five counts.\nThe first count charges sale to Joseph\nR. Beach. September 23. of a quantity\nof gin. The second charges possession\nof the gin sold on that occasion. The\nthird alleges a sale of gin to Benjamin\nF. Bean, September 25. In the fourth\ncount he Is charged with possession of\nthe gin sold to Bean. The fifth charge\nis a blanket allegation of possession of\n\"gin and alcohol\" in violation of the\nj national prohibition act.\nThe appeal in the Denison case prob\nably will b? heard during December In\nthe Court of Appeals, and a decision\nreached early in the new year. In the\ninterval Rover will continue to use the 1\nnew form.\nTHOUSAND BOY SCOUTS\nTO PRESENT PAGEANT\nLife of Washington Event to Be 1\nPart of National Celebration\nof Movement.\nMore than 1.000 Boy Scouts of the\nlocal council will participate in a pag\neant early in February depiciting the\nlife of George Washington. The event\nhere will be part of a Nation-wide cele\nbration on the twenty-first birthday of\nthe Boy Scout movement.\nThe scenes will include 14 imper\nsonations of Washington at different\nages, a pwo-wow of Virginia. Maryland\nand Pennsylvania Indians, a jollifica\ntion of the colored servants of Wash\nington's family and neighbors, Wash\nington's first birthday, a Virginia\nCounty fair in Washington\u2019s time and\nthe tutors of Washington in scout\ncraft. The place where the pageant\nwill be staged and the day will be de\ntermined later.\nCOURSE TO BE OPENED\nFOR BOYS AND GIRLS\nRally at Neighborhood House\nThursday Will Open Girls\u2019 Work\nCouncil Activity.\nThe Girls\u2019 Work Council of the\nRecreation Committee, Council of\nSocial Agencies, will conduct a course\nthis month to instruct young people\nin the leadership of boys\u2019 and girls\u2019\nclubs. The course will open Thursday\nwith a rally of leaders at the Neigh\nborhood House.\nDr. Paul Ewerhardt, director of the\nWashington Institute of Mental Hy\ngiene. will discuss child guidance be\nfore the leaders at 7:30 o'clock Tues\nday niglV, November 11. at the Y. W.\nC. A. On succeeding Tuesdays through\nout November, at the same time and\nplace, other speakers will address the i\nclass.\ni YOUNG MOFFETT AIRMAN\n_________\nSon of Admiral Completes Course\nand Will Go to Sea.\nEnsign George H. MofTett, son of\nRear Admiral William A. Moffett, chief\nof the Navy\u2019s Aeronautics Bureau, has\ncompleted a course at the Pensacoia\nNaval Air Station and will soon go to\nsea as an airman. Young Moffett will\nbe assigned to Carrier Division 2 of the\nI United States Fleet, which operates from\nSan Diego, Calif.\nAdmiral Moffett, who has been at the\nhead of naval aeronautics since 1921,\nobserved his sixty-first birthday Friday.\nPLAY IN CLUB BENEFIT\nFirst Lady Reserves Box for \u201cSub\nway Express,\u2019\u2019 Wellesley Event.\nThe Washington Wellesley Club will\nsponsor a mystery play, \u201cSubway Ex\npress,\u2019\u2019 at the National Theater tomor\nrow night for the benefit of the club\u2019s\nscholarship fund. Mrs. Herbert Hoover\nhas reserved a box for tiio performance.\nThe scofership is awarffsd for ex\ncellence in learning and has I%n ded\nicated to the memory of Mrs. Marion\nKinney Brookings who served to San\nFrancisqo under President Mover\nwhen ho was food administrator dflHng\nthe war.\nPAGE B-1\nHITS PROSECUTOR\nAND BALLISTICS IN\nCAMPBELL TRIAL\nBrother of Accused Charges\nAssistant District Attorney\n\u201cWent Beyond Duty.\u201d\nHOLDS BULLET TESTS\nUNRELIABLE IN COURT\nCall* on People of D. C. to Urg#\nReopening Cate of Convicted\nColored Man.\nThe Government ha* closed its book*\nin the case of the United States versus\nHerbert Campbell, with a final chapter\non the reliability of ballistics remaining\nincomplete.\nCol. Calvin H. Goddard of North\nwestern University, who was assigned to\nwrite the climatic chapter, reluctantly\nrelinquished the half-finished Job yes\nterday when the District attorney\u2019s of\nfice refused to hold the record open tot\nthe belated pages.\nAssistant United States Attorney Wil\nliam H. Collins, whose prosecution of\nCampbell on a charge of murdering\nMary Baker ended in the defendant\u2019s*\nexoneration, refused to co-operate with\nGoddard in a plan to finish the ballistic\nassignment in Chicago, and abandon-'\nment of the undertaking resulted.\nAs Col. Goddard was leaving late yes\nterday. Prank G. Campbell, brother of\nthe freed realty dealer, took a final fling\nat ballistic experts who claim their\nscience is \u201cexact\u201d and at the assistant\nDistrict attorney who brought his\nbrother to trial.\nScores Prosecutor.\nThe real estate man\u2019s brother held\nout two \u201clessons to be learned from thd\nCampbell murder case\u201d\u2014 first, that\nballistics is unreliable in trials for\ncapital offenses, and, second, that C\nprosecutor \u201cmay become an instrument\nof oppression and Justice rather than\nthe contrary.\u201d\nIncidentally, the brother referred to\na recent conviction of a colored man\nfor murder on evidence reportedly\n\"circumstantial and largely based upon\nballistic testimony\u201d and called on \u201cthe\npeople of the District of Columbia\u201d to\nreopen the case for an investigation of\nthe \u201csufficiency of the evidence\nBefore leaving for Chicago Col. God'\ndard turned over to Prosecutor Coiling\nthe 10 test bullets and five revolver*\nover which he had been working at the\nBureau of Standards. He reiterated his\nregret at Collins\u2019 refusal to consent to\na consummation of the ballistic experi\nment begun during the Campbell trial;\nand repeated his offer to conduct g\nsimilar test \u201cat any time\u201d to prove the\ninfallibility of bullet identification.\nCollins\u2022 Disapproves.\nIn a formal statement yesterday aft\nernoon, Goddard said that Collins had\ndisapproved his request for permission\nto appeal direct to Justice Jesse C.\nAdkins, presiding in Criminal Division\n2, for authority to finish the studies of\nthe exhibits in his Chicago laboratory.\nThe prosecutor explained that tha\nsole reason for refusing to agree to\nI continuation of the tests was that tha\nrecords in the Campbell case are\nclosed book\u201d and that \"no good pur\npose would be served\u201d by the tests now.\nPlans for a meeting last night of tha\nVeterans of Foreign Wars, at which Al\nH. Hamilton, defense criminologist\nwas to be introduced by Herbert Camp\nbell for the pupose of discussing bal\nlistics, failed to materialize. It was un\nderstood the meeting may be held to\nmorrow night or Tuesday night.\nTrial Will Coat $5,000.\nFrank Campbell said laat. night that\nthe trial will cost his brother between\n$3,500 and $5,000, in addition to his\nsorrow, worry and time.\u201d\n\u201cIt seems to me that there are two\noutstanding lessons to be learned from\nthe Campbell murder case,\u201d he said in\na statement issued yesterday. \u201cTh#\nfirst is that ballistics is far from being\nsuch an exact science as to Justify the\nsentencing to death of human beings\non the strength of it. and the second la\nthat prosecuting officials sometimes\nhave a very erroneous conception of\nwhat is required of them under what\nthey term their \u2018duty.\u2019\n\u201cWith respect to the question of\nwhere the duty of a prosecuting attor\nney lies, we had in the Campbell case\na situation where the prosecuting offi\ncials had before them before the ac\ncused was indicted a complete alibi\nbased upon written records that could\nnot possibly have been changed and\nwhich so completely establish the pres\nence of Herbert Campbell in his own\nhome at the time of the attack on Mlsa\nBaker as to make it a certainty that ho\ncould not possibly have been guilty. Yet\nwith this positive direct evidence in\nhand they proceeded to require the de\nfendant Campbell to place himself in\njeopardy and to go to the expense and\nthe humiliation of a murder trial mere\nly because they had certain circumstan\ntial evidence In hand.\nGoes Beyond Range of Doty.\n\u201cProsecuting officials become prose\ncuting officials because they have na\ntive ability In the way of eloquence, a\nconvincing manner of speech and a\nknowledge of the law. When they stand\nbefore a Jury these native advantages\nare buttressed and enhanced by the\nhalo which goes with a representative\nof the law. For such a man to stand\nbefore a jury of laymen, having little\nI knowledge of the law and urge the con\nj viction of a man whom he knows to be\nInnocent, merely because he thinks\nI that he can convict upon the cireum-\nI stantial evidence, seems to be going\nbeyond the range of duty.\n\u201cIf the newspapers are correct, a man\nwas recently indicted here in the Dis\ntrict of Columbia where the evidence\ni was wholly circumstantial and largely\nI based upon ballistic testimony. In\nthat case, according to the newspapers,\nthe defendant, an ignorant colored\nman. was confronted with the ballistic\nevidence and such other circumstantial\nevidence as had been accumulated. The\nofficers impressed upon him the cer\ntainty of conviction, whereupon he la\nsaid to have remarked, \u2018Well, I reckon\nyou have got enough to convict me and\nI had better take a 10 spot.\u2019\n\u201cThis, it seems, would make it clear\nthat he had been led to believe that\nif he would plead guilty he would get\noff with a 10-year sentence. When\nhe went to trial the remark quoted\nabove was, I am informed by the news\npaper men. construed to be equivalent\nto a confession and he was sentenced\nto imprisonment for life.\n\u201cIf the facts are as stated above, and\nif his remark, made merely with the\nthought that he would rather take a\nsentence of 10 years than to risk elec\ntrocution, was In fact twisted by the\nprosecution Into the equivalent of a\nconfession before a jury of, we know not\nwhat caliber, then the people of the\nDistrict of Columbia should not rest\nuntil that case is reopened and an in\nvestigation made of the sufficiency of\nthe evidence upon which this man '-as\nbeen sentenced to spend the rest of his\nnatural life In a penitentiary.\u201d","height":"25350","width":"19677"}}
